{{Infobox officeholder |image = |imagesize = |alt = |honorific-prefix = |name = Hugh Bold Gibb |honorific-suffix = |office = Unofficial Member of the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]] |term_start = 18 May 1866 |term_end = 11 November 1870 |predecessor = [[Thomas Sutherland (banker)|Thomas Sutherland]] |successor = [[Richard Rowett (businessman)|Richard Rowett]] |appointed = Sir [[Richard Graves MacDonnell|Richard MacDonnell]] |term_start1 = 29 May 1879 |term_end1 = 30 December 1879 |predecessor1 = [[Henry Lowcock]] |successor1 = [[Ng Choy]] |appointed1 = Sir [[John Pope Hennessy]] |birth_date = |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |party = |occupation = |alma_mater = |resting_place = |spouse = |religion = |signature = |footnotes = }} '''Hugh Bold Gibb''' was a British businessman in Hong Kong and China and member of the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]].
Gibb was a senior partner of the firm [[Gibb, Livingston & Co.]] from July 1855.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|work=The Hongkong Government|date=28 July 1855}}</ref> He was also director of the other companies including the China Fire Insurance Company.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=North China Herald|location=Shanghai|date=21 April 1870|title=Advertisement}}</ref> He was elected chairman of the [[Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce]] in 1864.<ref>{{cite web|title=Past Chairmen|url=http://www.chamber.org.hk/en/about/hkgcc_chairman_vice-chairman-8.aspx|work= The Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce}}</ref>
Gibb was appointed a member of the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]] in 1866 during the absence of [[Thomas Sutherland (banker)|Thomas Sutherland]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|work=The Hongkong Government|date=18 May 1866|number=74}}</ref> He served until 1871 when he resigned and was replaced by [[Richard Rowett]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|work=The Hongkong Government|date=13 July 1871|number=103}}</ref> He was appointed again to the Legislative Council in 1879 on the resignation of Henry Lowcock.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|work=The Hongkong Government|date=6 May 1879|number=111}}</ref> He was replaced by [[Ng Choy]] in 1880,<ref>{{cite news|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|work=The Hongkong Government|date=29 May 1880|number=130}}</ref> the latter becoming the first Chinese member of the Legislative Council on his appointment.
