'''Salah Ezzedine''' (born in 1962<ref>[http://www.liberation.fr/economie/0101590781-salah-ezzedine-le-madoff-libanais ''Liberation'': Salah Ezzedine, le «madoff» libanais] (in French)</ref> in South Lebanon) is a [[Lebanon|Lebanese]] businessman who is accused of running a [[pyramid scheme]]. He had supposed investments in oil, publishing, metals and television, and his businesses spread out from the Gulf to Africa.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1924186,00.html Andrew Lee Butters in ''Time'' magazine: Lebanon's Bernie Madoff - A Scandal Taints Hizballah]</ref> He was well known as a [[philanthropy|philanthropist]].
Before the fraud scandal occurred, he was known for his generosity and had even built a stadium and a mosque for his hometown of Maaroub.<ref>{{cite web|title=Time article|url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1924186,00.html|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref>
In the ensuing debacle, financial downfall and declaring of his bankruptcy, Lebanese investors, mostly from the Shia community lost hundreds of million dollars. Amounts involved vary between [[United States dollar|$]]700 million was lost by Lebanese investors<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/16/world/middleeast/16lebanon.html?scp=1&sq=ezzedine&st=cse Billion-Dollar Pyramid Scheme Rivets Lebanon]</ref> up to 1.2 billion dollars.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/fisk/lebanons-madoff-bankrupted-after-bouncing-200000-cheque-to-hizbollah-1783407.html Robert Fisk in ''The Independent'': 'Lebanon's Madoff' bankrupted after bouncing $200,000 cheque to Hizbollah]</ref>
