{{about||the Australian professional football (soccer) player|Scott Galloway}} {{Infobox person | image = | image_size = | name = Scott Galloway | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = November 3, 1964 (age 53) | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | restingplace = | nationality = [[Americans|American]] | religion = | ethnicity = | residence = [[New York City]] | education = | alma mater = [[Haas School of Business]] [[University of California, Los Angeles|University of California, Los Angeles]] | occupation = Professor, author, speaker, businessperson }}
'''Scott Galloway''' (born November 3, 1964) is a [[clinical professor]] of marketing at the [[New York University Stern School of Business]], and a [[public speaker]], [[author]], and [[Entrepreneurship|entrepreneur]].<ref name=Bruce>{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/brucerogers/2016/04/06/professor-turned-entrepreneur-founds-l2-to-benchmark-companies-digital-iq/#27502ac01b29 | title=Professor Turned Entrepreneur Founds L2 To Benchmark Companies' Digital IQ | newspaper=[[Forbes]] | first=Bruce | last=Rogers | date=6 April 2016 }}</ref><ref name=Betty>{{cite news| url=http://www.inc.com/betty-liu/this-entrepreneur-says-being-very-boring-is-going-to-make-you-very-rich.html | title=This Entrepreneur Says Being Very Boring Is Going to Make You Very Rich | newspaper=[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc.]] | first=Betty | last=Liu | date=11 July 2016 }}</ref>
== Career ==
In 2012, he was named one of the world's 50 best business school professors by Poets and Quants.<ref name="Carter">{{cite web | url=http://poetsandquants.com/2012/10/22/worlds-best-b-school-professors-scott-galloway/ | title=World’s Best B-School Professors: Scott Galloway | first=Andrea | last=Carter | date=22 October 2012 | publisher=Poets & Quants }}</ref> He was elected to the [[World Economic Forum]]'s "Global Leaders of Tomorrow", which recognizes 100 individuals under the age of 40 whose accomplishments have had impact on a global level.<ref name="NYU">{{ cite web | url=http://www.stern.nyu.edu/faculty/bio/scott-galloway | title=Scott Galloway - Professor of Marketing | publisher=[[New York University Stern School of Business]] }}</ref>
In 2005<ref name="Crunchbase"/> Galloway founded the digital intelligence firm [[L2 Inc]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Silverstein|first1=Sara|title=SCOTT GALLOWAY: Why you should worry about a company if its CEO is in a fashion magazine|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/scott-galloway-tech-ceo-image-snapchat-snap-evan-spiegel-tim-cook-sheryl-sandberg-2017-4?r=US&IR=T&IR=T|accessdate=23 April 2017|work=Business Insider|date=20 April 2017|language=en}}</ref> which was acquired in March 2017 by [[Gartner]],<ref name="Crunchbase">{{ cite web | url=https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/l2-inc#/entity | title=L2 Inc. | publisher=CrunchBase }}</ref> and the now defunct Firebrand Partners<ref>{{cite news|title=Investor group ready for New York Times proxy fight|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-newyorktimes-proxy-idUSN2150776520080222 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |date=22 February 2017}}</ref> (founded in 2005), an activist hedge fund that has invested over $1 billion in U.S. consumer and media companies.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McLean |first1=Bethany |title=Philip and Lisa Maria Falcone: Falcone Quest|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2011/07/falcones-201107|accessdate=23 March 2017 |work=The Hive |language=en}}</ref> In 1997, Galloway founded Red Envelope, one of the earliest e-commerce sites. In 1992, he founded [[Prophet (company)|Prophet]], a brand and marketing consultancy firm that employs over 400 professionals in the United States, Europe, and Asia.
He has served on the board of directors of [[Eddie Bauer]], [[The New York Times Company]], [[Gateway Computer]], [[Urban Outfitters]], and Berkeley's Haas School of Business. Galloway is also known for his public presentations<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carlson|first1=Nicholas|title=Here's The Deck On 'Winners And Losers' Hedge Fund Managers Are Begging To See|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/hedge-fund-managers-are-obsessed-with-this-presentation-on-the-biggest-winners-and-losers-in-digital-2014-9?IR=T|accessdate=23 March 2017|work=Business Insider|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Scott Galloway to Keynote at Catalyst Americas 2017|url=http://finance.yahoo.com/news/scott-galloway-keynote-catalyst-americas-133000508.html|accessdate=23 March 2017}}</ref> and [[TED (conference)|TED]]-style talks,<ref>{{cite web|title=A must Watch video: The 4 Giants by Scott Galloway {{!}} Stellar Search|url=http://www.stellarsearch.co.uk/2016/02/a-must-watch-video-the-4-giants/|website=Stellar Search|accessdate=23 March 2017|date=22 February 2016}}</ref> called ''Winners &amp; Losers'', in which he presents L2's Digital IQ Index<sup>&reg;</sup> results, ranking over 2,500 global brands<ref>{{cite news|last1=McGee|first1=Chantel|title=Amazon is becoming a 'more important search engine than Google,' says NYU professor|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/04/04/nyu-scott-galloway-amazon-becoming-bigger-search-engine-than-google.html|accessdate=23 April 2017|work=CNBC|date=4 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Loeb|first1=Walter|title=NYU Professor Scott Galloway Is Bearish On U.S. Retailing, Sees Global Opportunities|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/walterloeb/2017/05/08/nyu-professor-scott-galloway-is-bearish-on-us-retailing-see-global-opportunities/#1a0dfbd02f30|accessdate=10 May 2017|work=Forbes}}</ref> across numerous dimensions including [[e-commerce]], [[social media]], and [[digital marketing]].<ref name=DAISUKE>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/03/technology/google-lagging-amazon-races-across-the-threshold-into-the-home.html | title=Google, Lagging Amazon, Races Across the Threshold Into the Home | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |first=Nick WINGFIELD | last=Daisuke WAKABAYASHI | date=2 October 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Wingfield|first1=Nick|title=More Brands Mean Many More Buttons for Quirky Amazon Service|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/01/technology/amazon-widens-its-push-button-e-commerce-horizons.html|work=The New York Times|date=31 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hope|first1=Katie|title=How social media is transforming the fashion industry|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-35483480 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=5 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Dennis|first1=Steven|title=The Inconvenient Truth About E-Commerce: It's Largely Unprofitable |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/stevendennis/2017/03/17/the-inconvenient-truth-about-e-commerce/ |accessdate=17 March 2017|work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>
Galloway teaches brand management and digital marketing to second-year MBA students. Much of his research focuses on "The Four," or "the Four Horsemen." His first book, ''The Four: The Hidden DNA of Amazon, Apple, Facebook, and Google,'' was published in 2017. It analyzes [[Big Four tech companies|the four companies']] peculiar strengths and strategies, their novel economic models, their inherent rapacity, their ambition, and the drastic consequences of their rise that people face in both social and individual terms.
==Donations== An avid proponent of public education, Galloway donated $4.4 million to [[Haas School of Business]].<ref name="Markets Insider">{{ cite news | url=http://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/L2-Inc-Founder-Scott-Galloway-Donates-4-4m-for-Students-from-Immigrant-Families-to-UC-Berkeley-s-Haas-School-of-Business-1002379386 | title=L2, Inc. Founder, Scott Galloway, Donates $4.4m for Students from Immigrant Families to UC Berkeley's Haas School of Business | date=18 September 2017 | publisher=Markets Insider }}</ref> The son of immigrants, he designated the Galloway Fellows Fund<ref name="UC Berkeley">{{ cite press release | url=http://news.berkeley.edu/story_jump/alum-gives-4-4-million-for-scholarships-for-business-students-from-immigrant-families/ | title=Alum gives $4.4 million for scholarships for business students from immigrant families | author=Public Affairs, UC Berkeley | date=21 September 2017 }}</ref> to provide scholarships to students from immigrant families. He also announced gifts to [[UCLA]] and [[New York University]].<ref name="Markets Insider" />
